description: A film inspired by Nizar Qabbani's poem "Words" "He tells me, when he dances with me, Words are not like other words He takes me, from under my arms He plants me, in a distant cloud And the black rain in my eyes Falls in torrents, torrents He carries me with him, he carries me To an evening of rosy balconies And I am like a child in his hands Like a feather carried by the wind He gives me sun, he gives me summer and flocks of swallows He tells me that I am his treasure And that I am equal to thousands of stars And that I am treasure, and that I am more beautiful painting he has ever seen He tells me things that make me dizzy that make me forget the dance floor and the steps Words…which overturn my history which make me a woman…in seconds He builds castles of fantasies In which I live …for seconds… And I return…I return to my table Nothing with me… Nothing with me…except words Words are not like other words" Nizar Qabbani  Performing: Agnieszka Stach and Tymoteusz Ley cinematography: Damian Bartoszek postproduction: Jan Bożek, Damian Bartoszek, Agnieszka Stach, Tymoteusz Ley The film was shot in the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan. Locations: Amman (Roman Theatre, Jabal Al-Qal'a, Hashemite Plaza), Petra Archeological Park, Little Petra Bedouin Camp, Qasr Al-Kharana, Siq al-Barid (Little Petra), Desert.

description: Luis Bianchi & Daniela Pucci, intensive tango seminar "TURN ODYSSEY": Programme: A comprehensive exploration of turns in all their aspects: individual foundation work on posture, axis, weight transfers, pivots; the 3 geometrical possibilities for turns; dynamics (suspensions, drops and changes of speed); adding classical elements such as sacadas, ganchos and boleos; breaking away from the molinete to explore new, fully improvised options in the turn, including changes of direction.  ​

title: Tango: Roxana Suarez y Fernando Sanchez, 26/04/2015, Brussels Tango Festival - Remaster 2018-2020
description: Randomly mixed maestros tango performance by Roxana Suarez and Fernando Sanchez at Brussels Tango Festival 2015 on music "La foule" by Édith Piaf, 1957. Randomly mixed maestros dance 2/5, music select by DJ Valeria Norcia.  Remastered version of https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VdtqoOVo5Kk "Ramster 2018-2020" does not mean that I spent two years working on this. I don't remember precisely when was the first time when I had the idea to remaster this video. It could even be in 2016 or 2017. All I know is that I created the project file on 7th December 2018 and then worked on it very casually considering that it was not a priority. But in June 2020, as I finally got some more "focus time" than in the 10 previous months, and also got some delay working on the remaining Antwerpen Tango Festival 2019 videos, and as this one had remained a work in progress for so long, I decided that I wanted to finalise this one. The main issue I wanted to address was the light level going up and down, this could not be completely suppressed but could be attenuated in this remaster. I also found that the colours in original version felt a bit bland. It wasn't super easy to get more vivid colours without getting a yellowish taint or something else going wrong somewhere you don't expect but this remaster should have slightly more vivid colours. I've completely re-done the virtual re-framing as I'm now able to do it smoother than I did years before. I removed approximately 35 seconds of talking at the beginning of the videos. I reworked the sound, made the live sound a little louder, especially applause, but made the master volume a bit quieter to avoid saturation. This not a miracle remaster as you can see for some movies and some very old footages, and I don't think that this remake is perfect, but overall I think it is better than original version. title: Tango/zamba: Valeria Maside y Anibal Lautaro, 8/6/2019, Antwerpen Tango Festival 3/3 (2 camera edit)
description: Tango performance by Anibal Lautaro and Valeria Maside 3/3 at Antwerpen Tango Festival 2019 on music "Zamba para olvidarte" by Mercedes Sosa with Diego Torres and Facundo Ramírez, 2009. This version is "Two camera edit". "Four camera edit": https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y1sIvxKa0Lk&list=PLZj_Xxxg0Rkv5ob-ub1eYpAfV3glXk71g  This video is available in two distinct editings. What happened is that I first made an early version using cameras 1 and 2 which I usually use as "main" cameras. Then I inspected images of camera 5 (there was no camera 4 here) and it had many very well framed shots with dancers facing so that it made camera 5 interesting. Though, one problem with camera 5 in this festival is that for some reason it’s extremely grainy/noisy. The device that was used for this camera doesn’t belong to me so I didn’t do the settings myself and I have really no idea what went wrong, it’s supposed to be a quite good 4K camcorder but I suspect light sensitivity was set too high in some way. Additionally, though camera 5 had interesting sequences, using these forced more camera changes than I would have wished, and by the way, choosing more images from camera 5 results in hiding many good images with very different points of view from cameras 1 and 2. Yet, due to the inconstant colour lightings in the room, especially during this dance I find camera colour changes even more disturbing with extra cameras. (Regarding this, it seems beyond reach for any colour grading tool I use; I tested various options of black and white but I really didn’t like black and white for performance.) In usual cases, I would try to find a right balance to keep the "best of each world", but for this dance, considering the available images, I don’t think that balance can be obtained. Hence I decided to go for two versions: one using four of the five cameras and focusing on showing better close and detailed shots, implying somewhat more transitions, and a second with mostly based on cameras 1 and 2 aiming at following the dance with less cuts. And I expect that each video will feel very different from the other.  Something that was funny for me while editing… Valeria is not a singer as far as I know, but on some sentences of the song, I had the impression that Mercedes Sosa and Valeria had the same voice. And to add to this, on some shots you can see Valeria singing along, for example in the background shot in the end credits of the four camera version. title: Tango patchwork: Atheist peace (TC's tango mix)
description: If you enjoy the work (video), please support it: http://thomasconte.net/tango/donate/  YouTube release: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cCSTw5_D2KU  [FR, abrégé] (For EN, please see below.) Cette vidéo est une inspiration que j'ai eue dernièrement après avoir entendu une propagande guerrière religieuse particulièrement vomitive. C'est un patchwork de tango pas-tout-à-fait-tango comme j'en ai déjà faits. La chanson parle, je prends un racourci, de ne plus s'entretuer sur fond de religion. Comme d'habitude avec ce type de vidéo, je ne m'attends pas à ce qu'un large public y accroche facilement. Explications plus détaillées dans la version anglaise ci-dessous.  [EN] W.T.F. warning: This video patchwork is one of my inspirations after attacks and bombings in the name of religions in recent History. More precisely after hearing some disgusting religious war propaganda. This is as atypical and hermetic as my inspiration can go, so I don't expect many people to easily get into it. / I don't like to cheer on mass hysterias so you probably won't see me posting my emotions all over or changing some profile picture with some auto-generated flag or copy-pasted logos. Unless, I feel like creating something my own way. / I don't want this to have a strong link with Paris events, with a date or with anybody or anything precise. / This video patchwork is about being pissed off with murders in so-called service of religions still going on in the 21st Century. I don't truly mind what/if people believe as long as it is not used in some evil way. As opposed to "holy war", "atheist peace" is about getting free from religion enough not to fight or kill for it. / Lennon's "Imagine" would have been a safer bet for video's popularity, but that's too much of a cliché to get me inspired. / Though, let's not forget that religions are often used as make up for more complex geopolitical problems. / I think that armament is a bigger problem, actually.  I didn't ask the dancers otherwise this may never have been ready, and this is mostly composed of images that I have already released and that you can find in my tango video collection. Which means that there wasn't any dance/rhythm/opinion check done by the dancers.  It is recommended to have a coffee before watching.  T.C.  PS: Dancer list at the end of the video.  The contrasting introduction music is the start of one the best agnostic songs ever written ("Des gouttes de bonheurs" by French/Spanish singer Serge Utgé-Royo) so, if you understand, French I recommend you listen to the full version. Here is a live version: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eZZeHh14Qc0 , quite similar to the album version. (It hit me recently that this singer's voice has sometimes something of Alberto Podesta's voice, though not necessarily in this song as it is getting lower with years.)  The title screen holds references to Anti-Flag's "American spring", the Flying Spaghetti Monster and obviously some painting by Michelangelo di Lodovico Buonarroti Simoni in which angels all have a tattoo of Paul Simonon smashing a rifle instead of a bass guitar (as the Clash "London calling" album cover). I do not know who are the authors for the latter parodies as I simply found them on the web and assembled them. It has no canon interpretation so far, meaning is left up to viewers.  There is that sequence that looks like it is initiated by Marisa van Andel and Oliver Koch, continued by Vio TangoForge and Roberto l'Ange and closed by Noelia Hurtado and Carlitos Espinosa. It wasn't really planned, but since I noticed it I like that.  All parts of this video were shot in Full HD (1920x1080). YouTube version has been upscaled to UHD (3840x2160) because YouTube renders it better in this specific case. Even the re-downscaled HD version looks better. Do not ask me why, I don't know.

description: Tango patchwork made out of pieces of ICC Berlin shooting from the 17th January 2015. Note in 2019: I would re-do it but I would do some things differently now. With the time, I think the experimental mix #1 worked better.  With Vio: https://tangoforge.com Video by TC: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCPSEBKNWfeUQR22qpdYAIgg , http://thomasconte.net/tango/  If you enjoy the work (video), please support it: http://thomasconte.net/tango/donate/  At last, the third video from Berlin's ICC Sessions, with Vio TangoForge and some friends, is ready.  All details about and other ICC Session videos can be found here: http://thomasconte.net/tango/videos/20150117-tangoforge-icc-sessions/  This took forever ... If I remember well, this was the very first video project I started after I came back from Berlin in January 2015. But then I got the idea for "TangoForge ICC sessions #2 - TC's experimental mix #1" and wanted to finish it first, then it has been delayed due to "Brussels Tango Festival", Antwerpen Tango Festival" and a few other events with plenty of maestro videos to which I had to give priority because they are a lot less complex to edit. That and photography.  This is again an unplanned tango patchwork arranged on unusual music with a lot of accelerations. The concept here is very close to that of "TangoForge ICC sessions #2 - TC's experimental mix #1", except that it is not made of close-ups, and there is no "strobe trick" this time. Movements fit to music in some way, but there was no real intention to synchronise steps with beats ... Personally I still think rhythm is the most boring part of music!  This is also the first video in which I used the "Star Wars effects" that gave birth to the first version of "24/04/2015 Brussels Tango Festival - Marisa van Andel & Oliver Koch #2", though that one was ready approximately two months earlier. (I say "Star Wars effects" because that is how the software editor announced them in the upgrade note and some parts of them are dedicated to the production of lightsabers clash.)  The introduction sample is from, a band I think Vio has got some friend(s) in. It was part of the first soundtracks she suggested when we first talked of the idea of shooting video(s), though nothing was definitively set. I thought of doing a full video with it or something else from that band, but in the end I only used a sample that I think fits well to the main soundtrack.  Soundtrack/samples by "Matson Jones", "Anti-Flag" and "String Quartet tribute to Bad Religion".  Information about ICC sessions will be gathered on this page: http://thomasconte.net/tango/videos/20150117-tangoforge-icc-sessions/ or this page: http://tangoforge.com/icc-sessions/

Tango barre by Eleonora Kalganova
description: There is a vitality, a life force, an energy, a quickening that is translated through you into action, and because there is only one of you in all of time, this expression is unique. And if you block it, it will never exist through any other medium and it will be lost. The world will not have it. It is not your business to determine how good it is nor how valuable nor how it compares with other expressions. It is your business to keep it yours clearly and directly, to keep the channel open. You do not even have to believe in yourself or your work. You have to keep yourself open and aware to the urges that motivate you. Keep the channel open. ... No artist is pleased. [There is] no satisfaction whatever at any time. There is only a queer divine dissatisfaction, a blessed unrest that keeps us marching and makes us more alive than the others Martha Graham
